## What This Lab Simulates

This is not a generic networking lab. It simulates a real DoD-adjacent
production architecture used in an IL4/IL5 GovCloud environment. Every
design decision maps to a real operational requirement. Treat all work
as if it will be reviewed by a senior cloud security engineer.

### The Real Architecture Being Simulated

```
Customer browser (12,000+ customers, unmanaged devices, no client install)
      │
      │ HTTPS port 443
      ▼
ALB (internet-facing, VPC-B untrust subnet)
      │ TLS termination, WAF, ACM certificate
      ▼
Palo Alto VM-Series NGFW — UNTRUST ENI
      │ Layer 7 inspection, IPS, URL filtering, threat prevention
      │ source_dest_check = false (CRITICAL — Palo routes others' traffic)
Palo Alto VM-Series NGFW — TRUST ENI
      │ Inspected traffic exits toward AppGate
      ▼
AppGate SDP Portal appliance
      │ Clientless browser-based Zero Trust access
      │ Customer authenticates via MFA + IdP
      │ Portal performs Single Packet Authorization (SPA) on customer's behalf
      │ No AppGate client required on customer device
      ▼
AppGate Gateway
      │ Per-user encrypted micro-tunnel ("segment of one")
      │ Only entitled resources are reachable — everything else is invisible
      ▼
Customer's entitled resource
      │
      │ Return path:
      ▼
AppGate Gateway → Palo TRUST ENI → [inspect outbound] → Palo UNTRUST ENI
      │
      ▼
ALB → IGW → Internet → Customer browser

──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
MANAGEMENT PATH (separate, never crosses customer path):
A1 Windows (RDP) / A2 Linux (SSH) → TGW1 → Palo MGMT ENI
A1 / A2 → TGW1 → AppGate Controller
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
INTERNAL EGRESS (OS updates, license checks, IdP calls):
B1/C1/D1 → TGW → VPC-A → NAT Gateway → IGW → Internet
NAT Gateway is NOT in the customer traffic path.
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CLOUD HOST VISIBILITY (billing/SLA only):
VPC Flow Logs on VPC-A → CloudWatch
Cloud host reads flow logs for billing reconciliation and SLA reporting.
They do NOT inspect customer payload. Customer traffic never routes
through VPC-A. Flow logs give equivalent visibility to NAT logs
without adding a hop to the customer path.
```

### Key Architectural Invariants — Never Violate These

1. Customers NEVER reach VPC-A (Cloud Host). Enforced at TGW level —
   VPC-A and VPC-D share no Transit Gateway. No routing change can bridge them.
1. Palo Alto is the ONLY internet-facing component in the customer path.
   AppGate Portal, Gateway, and Controller are ALL private — no public IPs.
1. Customer traffic enters through Palo and returns through Palo.
   AppGate does NOT have a separate internet-facing path.
1. source_dest_check MUST be false on Palo UNTRUST and TRUST ENIs.
   Palo routes traffic not destined for its own IP. AWS drops such
   packets by default — disabling this check is mandatory, not optional.
1. NLB-C (fronting AppGate Portal) is internal-only.
   It is reachable from VPC-B trust side via TGW1, NOT from the internet.
1. The NAT Gateway handles only management/internal egress.
   It is never in the customer traffic path.

