# VPC-D — Customer Network Simulation (Lab Test Harness)

# 

# PURPOSE: Simulates a customer network onboarded via TGW

# attachment (Method 3 below). D1 is the test client used

# to validate that the security stack works as designed.

# 

# In production, real customers onboard via one of:

# 

# METHOD 1 — Browser/Portal (Primary method — 12k customers)

# No AWS networking changes needed per customer.

# Customer opens browser → portal.app.mil → authenticates

# via AppGate Portal → Portal performs SPA on their behalf

# → AppGate Gateway tunnels them to entitled resources.

# All onboarding work is in AppGate policy, not AWS.

# 

# METHOD 2 — Site-to-Site VPN (Customer on-prem network)

# Used when an entire customer organization network must

# be integrated, not just individual browser users.

# Provisions per customer:

# - aws_customer_gateway (customer’s public IP + ASN)

# - aws_vpn_connection (IPSec/BGP to Palo untrust ENI)

# Traffic flow: Customer network → VPN → Palo untrust ENI

# → [inspect] → Palo trust ENI → TGW1 → AppGate → resource

# 

# METHOD 3 — TGW Attachment (Customer has AWS environment)

# Customer AWS VPC attaches to TGW2 via RAM share.

# Their CIDR is added to TGW2 route table.

# Traffic flow: Customer VPC → TGW2 → Palo → AppGate

# → entitled resource → return path back through Palo.

# THIS IS WHAT VPC-D SIMULATES.

# Provisions per customer:

# - aws_ram_resource_share (share TGW2 with their account)

# - aws_ec2_transit_gateway_route (their CIDR in TGW2 RT)

# 

# ISOLATION GUARANTEE:

# VPC-A and VPC-D share NO Transit Gateway.

# There is physically no network path between them.

# No route table change, peering, or policy can bridge them.

# 

# WHAT THIS LAB VALIDATES:

# - D1 can reach Portal (NLB-C:443 returns 200)

# - Palo Alto is inline (no path to VPC-C bypasses VPC-B)

# - AppGate controls access (D1 cannot reach arbitrary IPs)

# - D1 cannot reach VPC-A (management isolation holds)

# - Return path works (curl responses return to D1)

